06788nam a22006735i 9780773574397DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735743977 a10.1515/97807735743972doi  a(DE-B1597)657571  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNX460 ǂb P74 2008eb 7aART0150002bisacsh04a700.9/0491 aAsselin, Olivier, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrecarious Visualities :bNew Perspectives on Identification in Contemporary Art and Visual Culture /cOlivier Asselin, Christine Ross, Johanne Lamoureux. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b51 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Precarious Visualities of Contemporary Art and Visual Culture -- t“Am I Still in the Picture?”: The Unsettling of Identification -- tSelf-Portraits -- tEnding Myths and the Catholic Outing of Andy Warhol -- tThe Persistence of Spectatorship: The Racialized and Ethnicized Gaze -- t“Are We Still in the Game?”: David Cronenberg’s eXistenZ -- tInterfaces of (In)Visibility -- tWhat the Body Remembers: Rebecca Belmore’s Memorial to Missing Women -- tThe Threshold of an Interface: Ilya Kabakov’s Looking up, Reading the Words (1997) -- tThe Star and the Prisoner: The Spectacle and Surveillance of the Self on the Web -- tThe Staging of Hallucination (of Hallucination) -- tHallucination as Ideology in Cinema -- tPara-Siting Visuality -- tMedia Image, Public Space, and the Body: Around Krzysztof Wodiczko’s Alien Staff -- tMediating Place-Identity: Notes on Mathias Woo’s A Very Good City -- tThe Polysensorialized Screen -- tJanine Antoni’s Lick and Lather: Eroticism as Identity Subversion -- tTelevisual Flesh: The Body, the Screen, the Subject -- tReal Time, Lived Time: ar Art, Perception, and the Possibility of the Event -- tThe Generating Image -- tThe Descent of the Image -- tResemblance and Identification: The Paradox of Gary Schneider’s Genetic Self-Portrait -- tVariations on Genetic Insignificant: Metaphors of the (Non)Code -- tAuthor Bios -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough the study of exemplary media works and practices - photography, film, video, performance, installations, web cams - scholars from various disciplines call attention to the unsettling of identification and the disablement of vision in contemporary aesthetics. To look at an image that prevents the stabilization of identification, identity and place; to perceive a representation that oscillates between visibility and invisibility; to relate to an image which entails a rebalancing of sight through the valorization of other senses; to be exposed, through surveillance devices, to the gaze of new figures of authority - the aesthetic experiences examined here concern a spectator whose perception lacks in certainty, identification, and opticality what it gains in fallibility, complexity, and interrelatedness. Precarious Visualities provides a new understanding of spectatorship as a relation that is at once corporeal and imaginary, and persistently prolific in its cultural, social, and political effects. Contributors include Raymond Bellour (École des hautes études en sciences sociales), Monika Kin Gagnon (Concordia University), Beate Ochsner (University of Mannheim -Universität Mannheim), Claudette Lauzon (McGill University), David Tomas (Université du Québec à Montréal), Slavoj Zizek (Ljubljiana University and University of London), Marie Fraser (Université du Québec à Montréal), Alice Ming Wai Jim (Concordia University), Julie Lavigne (Université du Québec à Montréal), Amelia Jones (University of Manchester), Eric Michaud (École des hautes études en sciences sociales), Hélène Samson (McCord Museum), and Thierry Bardini (Université de Montréal)."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aAsselin, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardini, Thierry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellour, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, Monika Kin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJim, Alice Ming Wai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Amelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamoureux, Johanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLamoureux, Johanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLauzon, Claudette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavigne, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichaud, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOchsner, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Christine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRoss, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSamson, Hélène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomas, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aŽižek, Slavoj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357439740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773574397423Coveruhttps://